entry.title: Redo page_load_in_process_fuzzer
entry.content:
This CL does several things to this fuzzer:



1) It didn't previously actually load pages when invoked against a

single testcase. For some reason in this circumstance,

LLVMFuzzerRunDriver calls the fuzz callback twice, so we tried to

load the page twice. By the second time, we had deleted the response.

2) It allows cross-origin test cases, by having several servers

available and allowing one body to refer to another.

3) It adds a seed corpus

4) It adds instructions for how to use this to reproduce some types of

issue often reported externally.

5) It fixes the logic which parsed the protobuf. This previously worked

when using a single test case, but didn't work when actually fuzzing.

The specific LoadTest function from libprotobuf-mutator must be used.

This change is abstracted out into the parent class for the benefit

of future in-process proto fuzzers.

entry.title: DOM: Introduce Subscriber#active attribute
entry.content:
This CL introduces an API, namely `subscriber.active` for determining

the activity of an existing subscription. The `active` attribute gets

set to false by the platform synchronously before the Observer's

completion and error handlers are invoked. This has the effect of being

observably `false` _within_ those handlers, unlike

`subscriber.signal.aborted`. Please see the lengthy design notes in both

https://github.com/WICG/observable/issues/76 and

https://github.com/WICG/observable/pull/82.

sometimes fail.



Root Cause:

- The variable timeAfterClick is really a time after pointerdown and can

possibly happen before the click event processingStart.

- LastInputTime is the timestamp of the event comes in. And when a new

event show up later, it will get refreshed.

- Thus, if we try to compare pointdown's processingEnd with

lastInputTime of (for example) click event, then there's no guarantee

of one is greater the other.



This CL address it by:

- Remove timeAfterClick, which is not a very meaningful timestamp, since

we should never assume no more events coming in after.

- Compare lastInputTime with the layout shift startTime instead, for

which the sequence is always guaranteed.

entry.title: [AW-IPP] Allow embedders to set IPP bypass policy
entry.content:
Currently, Chrome specific logic for bypassing IP Protection

exists in the underlying networking layers. The network stack

considers that first-party requests to top level frame will

not be IP Protected. While this is true for Chrome, this is

not in line with WebView's policy. Architecturally, network

stack (or other underlying layers) should be agnostic to

embedder specific logic.



This CL refactors the network stack in such a way that the

network stack support multiple bypass policies and allows

the embedder to set the policy it requires using the general

interfaces provided to plumb data between the layers

in Chromium.



Additionally, some minor clean up is also done along the way.

(e.g. making tests adhere to go/gunitfaq).

entry.title: DOM: Separate Observer#signal and Subscriber#signal
entry.content:
Before this CL, the AbortSignal passed into the Observer dictionary is

piped through directly to the Subscriber, to live on

`Subscriber#signal`. This is problematic because many people will pass

this signal directly through to underlying sinks that produce data that

the Observable will push to the Subscriber, however this signal will not

be aborted by producer-initiated cancellations, i.e., `complete()` and

`error()`.



This CL fixes this problem by initializing `Subscriber#signal` as a

"dependent signal" [1], which exists in the DOM Standard for exactly

this reason. This is necessary because we can't just make `complete()`

and `error()` signal "abort" on the AbortSignal passed into

`subscribe()`, because this would trigger abort algorithms and event

handlers *unrelated to the subscription* to be triggered.



[1]: https://dom.spec.whatwg.org/#create-a-dependent-abort-signal

entry.title: Make sure we are not matching a URL only on No-Vary-Search hint
entry.content:
`no_vary_search::IterateCandidates` matches nav URL with prefetch URLs

without query params and fragment parts and returns the prefetch

container as `no_vary_search::MatchType::kOther` matches.



In `PrefetchService::FindPrefetchContainerToServe`, if the

`no_vary_search::MatchType::kOther` prefetch has No-Vary-Search hint

and matches, then we are returning it. This is incorrect, as, in the case where the prefetch already got its head without a No-Vary-Search

response header we are basically skipping No-Vary-Search header

validation. In this specific case, if the prefetch had a No-Vary-Search header, the prefetch should have been marked as `no_vary_search::MatchType::kNoVarySearch` instead.



We can return prefetch marked `no_vary_search::MatchType::kOther`

in `PrefetchService::FindPrefetchContainerToServe` only if they are

still in progress and we are still waiting for the response head.





Bug: 1416659

entry.title: Replace the MPC entry on partial hits.
entry.content:
Instead of letting the old entry stay in the cache, we replace it

as long as we didn't have a full hit. This has two immediate

positive effects:



- We get more full MPC hits, as more recent ComputedStyles are more

likely to get full matches (most likely, we would have irrelevant

entries being stuck forever).



- After the last CL (Fix comparison of inherited variables in MPC),

we would have to compare a ComputedStyle's StyleInheritedVariables

against both the old style's and the one in the MPC; this would

trash the partner cache (accelerating operator==) since we'd do

repeated comparisons over and over again. Replacing the entry

in the MPC makes it more likely that the two StyleInheritedVariables

instances are the same, and the partner cache then helps again.

entry.title: Fix comparison of inherited variables in MPC.
entry.content:
On an MPC partial hit, if both parents had inherited custom properties,

we'd compare these inadvertently by pointer instead of value. If we had

a recalc that involved constructing the StyleVariables object because

the element they were on was recalculated (like in the style perftest,

which always invalidates from the root), this would cause us to always

get a mismatch and then always think we needed to reapply inherited

properties.



Of course, the MPC should probably at some point get replaced with the

new StyleVariables object, but we're not modifying the replacement
